NBA PLAYERS SALARY ANALYSIS

Kevin Andrian Suryanto

Abstract

A common person would assume that the success of an NBA players career is directly correlated with how much points they can score, and therefore would earn more salary if they have more points. However, points scored by an NBA player typically arent the only measure of success. Moreover, although some NBA players are considered more successful than others, some of those players identified as less successful earn more than some players that are indentified as more successful.

Research Question

What affects an NBA players salary? What are the biggest contributing factors to a players salary? Does more playing time result in higher salary?

Packages needed

library(magrittr)
library(dplyr)
library(tidyverse)
library(DataComputing)

Data for Analysis

nbastats <- read.csv("nba_2017_players_stats_combined.csv")
nbasalary <- read.csv("nba_2017_salary.csv")

These 2 datasets are obtained from Kaggle (https://www.kaggle.com/noahgift/social-power-nba), an online community of data scientists and machine learning practitioners. The data is collected by the NBA and uploaded by Noah Gift in 2017. This data is used in several studies for the IBM Developerworks: Explore valuation and attendance using data science and machine learning and Exploring the individual NBA players.

Variables

  • Rk = Players rank in terms of points per game
  • PLAYER = Players name
  • POSITION = Players position
  • AGE = Players age
  • MP = Minutes played
  • FG = Field goals made per game
  • FGA = Field goals attempted per game
  • FG. = Field goal % (made over attempted)
  • X3P = 3-point field goals made per game
  • X3PA = 3-point field goals attempted per game
  • X3P. = 3-point field goal % (made over attempted)
  • X2P = 2-point field goals made per game
  • X2PA = 2-point field goals attempted per game
  • X2P. = 2-point field goal % (made over attempted)
  • eFG. = Effective field goal %
  • FT = Free throws made per game
  • FTA = Free throws attempted per game
  • FT. = Free throw % (made over attempted)
  • ORB = Offensive rebounds per game
  • DRB = Defensive rebounds per game
  • TRB = Total rebounds per game
  • STL = Steals per game
  • BLK = Blocks per game
  • TOV = Turnovers per game
  • PF = Personal fouls committed per game
  • Points = Points per game
  • TEAM = Players team abbreviation
  • GP = Number of games played
  • MPG = Minutes played per game]
  • ORPM = Offensive real plus-minus per game
  • DRPM = Defensive real plus-minus per game
  • RPM = Real plus-minus per game
  • WINS_RPM = An estimate of the number of wins a player has contributed to his teams win total on the season
  • PIE = Players impact estimate (a players impact on each individual game they play)
  • PACE = Estimate of the number of possessions per 48 minutes
  • W = Number of wins
  • SALARY = Amount of yearly salary (in $)

Glimpse of Data

head(nbastats)
head(nbasalary)

The variable POSITION and TEAM will be deleted from nbasalary since POSITION and TEAM are already present in the nbastats dataset. The first colum will be deleted from nbastats since it is unnecessary. The two datasets will be joined by the players name. Duplicates of NBA players (if any) will also be removed.

nbastats <- nbastats[,-1]
nbasalary <- nbasalary[,-2][,-2]
nba <- nbastats %>%
  left_join(nbasalary, by = c("PLAYER" = "NAME"))
Column `PLAYER`/`NAME` joining factors with different levels, coercing to character vector
nba = nba[!duplicated(nba$PLAYER),]
head(nba)

Data Description

The dataset nbastats" shows statistics for NBA players on-court performances in the 2016-2017 season. The dataset nbasalary shows NBA players salaries in the 2016-2017 season. The combined dataset has 446 cases. Each case represents an NBA player.

nrow(nba)
[1] 446

Does an NBA players points result in higher salary?

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=POINTS,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of PPG (figure 1.1)")

When referring to figure 1.1, there seems to be an upward trend which shows that higher points per game typically results in higher salary although its not for all cases.

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=POINTS,y=SALARY))+geom_point()+facet_wrap(~POSITION,ncol=4) + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of PPG per position (figure 1.2)")

According to figure 1.2, higher points result in higher salary amongst all player positions. Furthermore, we will observe how other key NBA stats affect a players salary.

Assists per game

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=AST,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of APG (figure 2.1)")

We can obseve that there is an upward trend in salary in terms of assists per game.

Rebounds per game

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=TRB,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of RPG (figure 2.2)")

We can obseve that there is an upward trend in salary in terms of rebounds per game.

Steals per game

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=STL,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of SPG (figure 2.3)")

We can obseve that there is a slight upward trend in salary in terms of steals per game although it is not significant.

Blocks per game

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=BLK,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of BPG (figure 1.1)")

We can obseve that there is a slight upward trend in salary in terms of blocks per game although it is not significant.

Minutes played per game

ggplot(data=nba,aes(x=MP,y=SALARY))+geom_point() + stat_smooth(method=lm) + ggtitle("Salary of NBA players in terms of MPG (figure 2.5)")

We can obseve that there is an upward trend in salary in terms of minutes played per game.

However, although all of these key NBA stats graphically show an increasing trend, we will further perform a simple linear regression test the significance of these NBA statistic measures.

Simple Linear Regression

Linear regression models are used to show or predict the relationship between two variables or factors. We will fit salary as the response variable and use number of points, assists, rebounds, steals, blocks, and minutes played as the predictors.

summary(model)

From the p-value results above, we are 95% confident that number of points, assist, and rebound have a significant relationship with a players salary. However, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that steals, blocks, and minutes player significantly affect a players salary.

Conclusion

From the graphical and linear regression observations, we can conclude that the number of points per game by an NBA player significantly affects an NBA players salary. Moreover, other key important factors such as number of assists and rebounds also significantly affect a players salary. Some people may say that more playing time (or minutes played) have higher salaries. However, although our graph shows that there is a positive relationship between minutes played and salary, the linear regression output shows that the effect of minutes played is not significant to salary.
